post_text: Swanville Schools has been working with a program called Positive Behavioral Interventions and Supports (PBIS) during the 2019-2020 school year. We plan on implementing this program beginning with the first day of school in 2020-2021. Part of this involved developing some core values, which we have called Bulldog Heart. Heart stands for Helping Everyone Achieve Responsibility Together. We have developed a set of expectations for student behavior. There will be posters and signs throughout the school with these expectations, More information, and these expectations are on the school website. Look for the tab PBIS under the district drop down.

post_text:
The school board met last night and has decided that to begin the school year, as of right now, we will be doing in-person learning with all students in the building. This decision is based on a number of factors, please see our website, www.swanville.k12.mn.us for more information and a full letter from Superintedent Harthan and the first version of our Back To School 20/21 plan. Families may still opt to do distance or hybrid learning. Also, we ask that you fill out the survey found at this link: https://forms.gle/srjap1Rqs19o3aUZA
Please do so before midnight on Saturday August 15th.
This is a very difficult situation for all of us. We know that decisions made will never please everyone. We are doing our best to look out for everyone's best interest. We ask that you put aside your opinions and support us as a district and most importantly your students. They are listening.

post_text:
As many of you have heard by now, MSHSL voted today to move Volleyball and Football to the Spring with a March start.

For now the following Fall seasons remain: cross country, tennis, & swimming
Winter seasons remain the same
3rd season - start Mid March to Mid-May: Volleyball and Football. These seasons will include no scrimmages, shorter season, fewer games, with postseason to be determined.
4th season - start May until early July will include: baseball, softball, & track.

Junior High and youth Sports are not governed by the MSHSL so weren't included in anything you might read.

As we receive more information, it will be promptly passed along.

The MSHSL was in a very difficult position and was looking out for the safety and health of everyone. Whether you agree or disagree, negative talk about this won't help the matter. The fall seasons could have been cancelled all together, at least this gives some sort of season for the football and volleyball athletes. Please try and refrain from negative talk about the MSHSL decision.

post_text: Governor Walz today announced several scenarios under which school may begin the school year. At this point, Swanville falls in the category where all students can go back to school in the building, but need to be prepared to switch to hybrid or distance learning if conditions change. We have been working on plans for in-school, hybrid and distance learning. The school board is meeting next week and we will have a final announcement about what we plan to do by the end of next week, August 6th or 7th.

post_text: We will be offering the classroom portion of driver's education July 6th-10th, and July 13th-17th. The class will run from 8:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. The make up day for hours missed will be July 20th. State law requires 30 hours of classroom instruction. Depending on what happens with the government opening things back up and how many students we get, will determine how this will run. Some of it may require some days of actual in the building instruction and alternate days of meeting through Zoom. In essence, half of you in the building one day and the other half the next. This will allow us to run the class and accommodate the maximum number of students. You must be 15 by September 1st to take the class. Please let Mrs. Johnson know if you plan on taking this as soon as possible so we can begin our planning.

post_text: The Swanville School District and community are saddened to learn of the passing of Connor Throener, a 17-year-old Junior at Swanville High School. Connor was unable to recover from his injuries suffered in a tragic car accident. It is even more difficult for everyone during this pandemic, as people are not as able to get together in large groups to grieve. Connor will live on in many lives and continue to touch people with his generous spirit, as Connor had made the decision to be an organ donor. Our deepest sympathies go out to Connor’s family at this time. Keep them in your thoughts and prayers. We have listed some resources for parents and students to reach out to as we all struggle through this difficult time. We have also included some resources to read through on our district website-www.swanville.k12.mn.us

April 20, 2020

Good Morning K-2! We are still unsure what the rest of the year will look like, but in preparation for distance learning for the remainder of the year, we are asking you to bring the drawstring bag back to school. We will be washing these, repacking them, staff will be wearing gloves. We will return the same bag to the same student. We will have a container (labeled bag drop off) set outside of the back parking lot /common doors. This container will be available starting today through April 24 (morning/night). We would like these bags by the end of the week (Friday April 24th by 3pm) so we can start packing for May! We will give you more information as we learn it!

Thank you and stay healthy,
K-2 teachers

Each field will be on for 181 minutes which combines for a total of 362 minutes, 1 minute for each of our students pre K - 12th grade.

post_text:
ATTN: UPDATED K-2 Attendance Policy

Starting Thursday, April 2
Please send a DAILY text, Remind, or Email to your child’s classroom teacher between 8:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m. for attendance. Include your child’s name as the subject. If we do not hear from you by 2:00 pm, your child will be marked absent for the day. If your child’s daily work is completed by 2:00 pm, you can send pictures and this will count as attendance.

Your child’s DAILY work will still need to be sent by 8:00 p.m, for tracking progress. If you send work after office hours, 8 to 3 p.m. you will get a response on the next school day.

Thank you for your patience and flexibility! We are all in this together and you are doing great!

IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS PLEASE CALL YOUR CHILD’S CLASSROOM TEACHER.

Grades 3 through 12 please check in with your designated teacher by noon daily.

post_text:
Good afternoon Swanville families and welcome to day 1 of distance learning across the state. We hope by now all students in grades 3 through 12 have checked in with either their homeroom teacher in grades 3 through 6 or your second hour teacher in grades 7 through 12. Just a reminder you will need to do that daily when school is in session. If you are having any issues, please contact your teacher or the main office and we will do our best to help.

Some updates on events. Prom has been postponed on the April 18th date. We are looking at May 16th as a possible new date, depending on what happens with orders from the government. Please know if this would also be postponed that we will still try and make prom happen. The senior class trip is a wait and see, as is the Lions Senior Honor Banquet. As of now, graduation is still slated for May 22nd at 8 p.m.

Easter break is still on for Thursday April 9th, Friday April 10th and Monday April 13th. We will not provide the following services on those days: meal delivery, daycare, classroom instruction.

March 20th Update
Swanville Families,

Happy Friday! What a week this has been! Just a quick update today! We are working diligently on our distance learning plan and are happy to say it is coming along nicely! If you are not enrolled in meals but need to, please contact Deb Hollermann.

We are happy to see the great response to Mr. Harthan’s video, please also see the page for Ms. Amanda’s video to the young kiddos & Mr. Gapinski’s video from today.

Be sure to “Like” our page and share it with other families so we can all stay up to date on communication.

As always, let us know if you have any questions or concerns! Lastly, THANK YOU to each and everyone of you parents, students, staff, administration, board and community members for working through Week ONE! #swanvillestrong

Enjoy your weekend!

post_text:
MARSHMALLOW IGLOOS
1st graders have enjoyed STEM activities (Science, technology, engineering, math). 1st grade met with their 4th grade friends to make a list of "materials" needed to build an igloo with marshmallows. Then, they had to draw a model of their igloo. The following day, students were given the requested supplies to build. It was fun to see their imagination and the different ways to construct an igloo.

post_text: Our 4th, 5th and 6th grade students will be attending BizTown next week as the capstone in their Junior Achievement experience. They have been very busy preparing including 4 students that ran for mayor, having elections and job interviews. Our mayoral candidates gave speeches and had to answer questions in a town hall style setting. Student also had to apply for and interview for a wide variety of jobs at the businesses that will be part of BizTown. Lastly, they had to vote on a mayor, congratulations to Warner Pechan Klemish. We are so looking forward to this experience next week!

post_text:
Art Student of the Month -

NEW!! Beginning January 2020, Swanville Schools will be starting the “Art Student of the Month” award. Art SOM will give recognition to a student (grades 7 -12) that shows excellence and distinction in the visual arts. There are many students in our school community that deserve to be commended for their commitment to creating beautiful works of art!

Zavanna Holmquist -

Zavanna has been chosen as January’s Art Student of the Month. Zavanna is a very talented artist, and she is especially skilled at drawing. Along with using the proper drawing methods, Zavanna puts a lot of emotion and meaning into her drawings! This is what makes her work so compelling and interesting to look at. It can sometimes be difficult to express your emotions through art, but Zavanna does it in a way that speaks to a lot of people.

post_text:
Pictured are the two winners of the 19/20 Lions Peace Poster Contest from Swanville Schools with Dandee Lions President Sheryl Johnson. Ethan Barthel took first place and won $100 and Mya Proell was the second place winner. She was awarded $50 for her efforts. The posters will go on to the district to be judged. The 2019-2020 Contest has the following theme-History has shown that all too often peace is not guaranteed. While this is unfortunate, it also allows us the powerful opportunity to figure out how to achieve peace, individually and in our communities. And who better to map out the “Journey of Peace” than our youth?
Ethan's poster is of the globe with the two hands reaching across and Mya's is of the two hands linked by pinkies. Congratulations to both!
text:
Pictured are the two winners of the 19/20 Lions Peace Poster Contest from Swanville Schools with Dandee Lions President Sheryl Johnson. Ethan Barthel took first place and won $100 and Mya Proell was the second place winner. She was awarded $50 for her efforts. The posters will go on to the district to be judged. The 2019-2020 Contest has the following theme-History has shown that all too often peace is not guaranteed. While this is unfortunate, it also allows us the powerful opportunity to figure out how to achieve peace, individually and in our communities. And who better to map out the “Journey of Peace” than our youth?
Ethan's poster is of the globe with the two hands reaching across and Mya's is of the two hands linked by pinkies. Congratulations to both!

post_text: The preschoolers have completed their service learning project “Cookies for the Community.” They collected change, went to the bank to watch the change machine and were excited to get $224 to make cookies. They went to the grocery store to purchase ingredients, helped mix up the cookies and teachers baked them. Each preschooler signed up for a local business to deliver cookies with their family and say “Thanks” by GIVING to our community members who are so supportive of our school.

post_text: This is being offered at Swanville Schools. BARRE is a combination of Pilates, Yoga, and Ballet. This class will improve your posture, balance, and core strength. If you love yoga, you will truly love BARRE! Whether you are a beginner or a workout enthusiast, you will be amazed by the different muscles you will use. Starting Nov 1st in the Swanville old gym, ending April 30th. Instructor: Jen Albright, certified BARRE and Yoga Instructor, 320-979-8127. Cost: $30 per month or $50 for a 10 session punch card. Class times: Monday and Wednesday evenings at 7:15 PM. To register, come to class on Nov 4th.”
